# Three long and six short

Remote working is often presented as a perfect solution, but in reality it can introduce a range of challenges that make collaboration slower, communication less clear, and team cohesion much harder to maintain over time without deliberate effort.
When people are not physically present in the same space, it becomes significantly more difficult to pick up on nuance, resolve issues quickly, and build the informal relationships that support effective teamwork in complex organisations.
As a result, organisations that rely too heavily on remote arrangements without putting strong structures in place may find that productivity suffers and employees feel increasingly disconnected from both their work and their colleagues.
Remote work sounds ideal. It reduces commuting time. People enjoy flexibility. Communication becomes harder. Meetings take longer.
Teams can feel isolated.